{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:41:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:41:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13659"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13659"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.16,0.39,0.08,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54107"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6264"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13659"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39579"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1880"},{"type":"tags","id":"1956"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2571"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"5808"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16308"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54107"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the paediatric clinic with a six-month history of increasing shortness of breath. His parents report that over the same period he has been experiencing frequent headaches and dizziness. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears cyanosed. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 85% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a grade 3/6 holosystolic murmur at the left lower sternal border and a middiastolic murmur. There is clubbing of his fingers and toes. A chest X-ray shows mild cardiomegaly. An echocardiogram shows a large septal defect with right-to-left shunting and evidence of severe pulmonary hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is this patient most at risk of developing without appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary stenosis","Aortic regurgitation","Secondary erythrocytosis","Mitral stenosis","Pulmonary atresia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario describes a patient with signs and symptoms consistent with Eisenmenger syndrome. This condition occurs when a longstanding left-to-right cardiac shunt caused by a congenital heart defect (suggested by the holosystolic murmur and mid diastolic murmur indicative of a ventricular septal defect) leads to pulmonary hypertension and eventually causes a reversal of the shunt direction to right-to-left, resulting in cyanosis and hypoxemia. \u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary erythrocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common complication in patients with Eisenmenger syndrome due to chronic hypoxemia. The body compensates for low oxygen levels by producing more red blood cells, leading to an increased hematocrit. This condition can cause hyperviscosity symptoms such as headaches, dizziness, and increased risk of thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically a congenital heart defect where the pulmonary valve is narrowed, impeding blood flow from the right ventricle to the pulmonary artery. It is not a complication of untreated septal defects with Eisenmenger syndrome. The patient\u0027s symptoms and findings (e.g., clubbing, cyanosis, right-to-left shunting) do not suggest pulmonary stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E involves the backflow of blood from the aorta into the left ventricle due to improper closure of the aortic valve. It is unrelated to the progression of a septal defect to Eisenmenger syndrome. The patient\u0027s murmur and echocardiogram findings are more consistent with septal defect complications rather than aortic valve pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitral stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by narrowing of the mitral valve, leading to obstructed blood flow from the left atrium to the left ventricle. It is not a typical complication of untreated septal defects with Eisenmenger syndrome. The patient\u0027s symptoms, including pulmonary hypertension and right-to-left shunting, do not align with mitral stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary atresia\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital condition where the pulmonary valve does not form properly, preventing blood from flowing from the right ventricle to the lungs. This condition is present at birth and not a complication of septal defects with Eisenmenger syndrome. The patient\u0027s history of worsening symptoms and current findings of severe pulmonary hypertension and right-to-left shunting indicate Eisenmenger syndrome, not pulmonary atresia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A ventricular septal defect (VSD) is a common congenital heart defect that can lead to Eisenmenger syndrome if left untreated.","Eisenmenger syndrome results in the reversal of the left-to-right shunt, leading to cyanosis and secondary erythrocytosis due to chronic hypoxemia.","Recognizing and treating VSD early is crucial to prevent complications such as pulmonary hypertension and Eisenmenger syndrome."],"references":["Arvanitaki A, Giannakoulas G, Baumgartner H, Lammers AE. Eisenmenger syndrome: diagnosis, prognosis and clinical management. Heart. 2020 Nov 1;106(21):1638-45. https://heart.bmj.com/content/106/21/1638.abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39579"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13659"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39579"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-30T13:27:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-30T15:11:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6264"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54107"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationship